article.headline: Carter's double-double aids rout
article.linkText: LaTech near perfect in burying Tulane
article.story: RUSTON, La. (AP) -- Every head coach yearns for perfection. Kurt Budke nearly got it Tuesday night from his Louisiana Tech players. The Lady Techsters (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today; No. 11 AP) were clicking all around, played everybody but the student managers and cruised to a 96-37 rout over Tulane. "You always look for perfection and this was about as close as you could get to it," the second-year coach said. "I was really, really pleased with the way we played and our effort the entire night. Offensively and defensively, you couldn't ask for much more." Amber Obaze scored 18 points, and Amisha Carter added 15 points and 14 rebounds. Tech (3-0) dominated the game from start to finish, going up by 30 or more points during the final 7½ minutes of the opening half and prevailing by 40-plus points after the break against Tulane (1-3). Obaze was 8-for-13 from the floor and 2-for-3 from the line. The Techsters also got 16 points from Trina Frierson. The Techsters hit on 54.3 percent of their shots, going 38-of-70. On the boards, Tech had a 43-30 advantage. It marked the seventh time in as many tries that Tech has won over Tulane, a team that has appeared in the last nine NCAA postseason tournaments. "We don't take anybody lightly and we sure didn't with them because they've had some good teams there," Frierson said. "Just because they had a losing record didn't mean we weren't going to be ready for them. We prepared for them just like we do anybody else." Tulane was led by Lakethia Hampton's nine points. "Tech has another great team and they made it difficult for us to get into any kind of rhythm," Tulane coach Lisa Stockton said. "They controlled the game early with their defensive effort and forced us into a lot of turnovers. Offensively, they shot the ball well and did a great job scoring from both inside and outside."
